    "body_text": [
        {
            "text": "Evaluation for resolution of FPIES by oral food challenge should be deferred until the COVID-19 pandemic resolves to minimize the risk of acute reactions.",
            "cite_spans": [],
            "section": "Evaluation for resolution of FPIES ::: Introduction of new foods",
            "ref_spans": []
        },
        {
            "text": "Patients with detectable food-specific IgE antibody via skin prick test or serologic measurement, are referred to as atypical FPIES. The majority of these patients exhibit classic FPIES symptoms during reactions but a small subset might transition to immediate symptoms such as hives, skin rashes, or very rarely, anaphylaxis. Depending on the physician assessment of the likelihood of an immediate-IgE mediated reaction, emergency medications may be prescribed and management of anaphylaxis discussed proactively (2).",
            "cite_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 515,
                    "end": 516,
                    "mention": "2",
                    "ref_id": "BIBREF1"
                }
            ],
            "section": "Atypical FPIES ::: Introduction of new foods",
            "ref_spans": []
        },
        {
            "text": "Patients with FPIES have high rates of allergic comorbidities, including IgE-mediated food allergy to foods other than FPIES triggers, asthma, atopic dermatitis, allergic rhinitis, and eosinophilic esophagitis. (5). It is important to maintain optimal control of these comorbid conditions during the COVID-19 pandemic.",
            "cite_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 212,
                    "end": 213,
                    "mention": "5",
                    "ref_id": "BIBREF4"
                }
            ],
            "section": "Managing comorbidities ::: Introduction of new foods",
            "ref_spans": []
        },
        {
            "text": "FPIES poses a great burden for the patients and caregivers under usual circumstances. To address the added stress of the COVID-19 pandemic, limited access and supply of safe foods, and anxiety about potential reactions, the International FPIES Association website (www. fpies.org) provides valuable advice for day-to-day management of FPIES and can be utilized as an important educational resource to complement medical management of FPIES.",
            "cite_spans": [],
            "section": "Resources for the patients and caregivers ::: Introduction of new foods",
            "ref_spans": []
        },
        {
            "text": "In summary, effective management of FPIES during the COVID-19 pandemic requires modification of the existing treatment paradigm to minimize the need for emergency department intervention and reduce risk of acquiring COVID-19.",
            "cite_spans": [],
            "section": "Resources for the patients and caregivers ::: Introduction of new foods",
            "ref_spans": []
        },
        {
            "text": "Stefania Arasi, MD, Ashis V Barad, MD, Theresa Bingemann, MD, Terri Brown-Whitehorn, MD, Raquel Durban, MS, RD, LD/N, Todd Green, MD, George Konstantinou, MD, Stephanie Leonard, MD, Jennifer Lightdale, MD, Antonella Muraro, MD, PhD, Ichiro Nomura, MD, PhD, Jonathan Spergel, MD, PhD, Carina Venter, RD, PhD",
            "cite_spans": [],
            "section": "Resources for the patients and caregivers ::: Introduction of new foods",
            "ref_spans": []
        }
